\textbf{Manual Solution}: Notice that there is a $7+8+9$ in the numerator and a $9+8+7$ in the denominator. Cancel these, leaving $\frac{6+9+12}{2+3+4}$. At this point, simply perform the addition to get $\frac{27}{9}$, which equals $\boxed{3}$.\newline

\frac{7+8+9}{2+3+4} &= \frac{24}{9} \\
&= \frac{8}{3}.
\end{align*}Next, we evaluate the fraction on the right: \begin{align*}
\frac{6+9+12}{9+8+7} &= \frac{27}{24} \\
&= \frac{9}{8}.
\end{align*}The value of the entire expression is then: \begin{align*}
\frac{8}{3}\cdot \frac{9}{8} &= \frac{(8\cdot9)}{(3\cdot1)} \\
&= \frac{72}{3} \\
&= \boxed{24}.\end{align*}\newline
